{{Infobox medical person | honorific_prefix = | name = Mary Agnes Snivley | honorific_suffix = | image = Mary Agnes Snively.png | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name above --> | birth_date = {{birth date|1847|11|12}} | birth_place = [[St. Catharines]], [[Ontario]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1933|09|26|1847|11|12}} | death_place = | death_cause = | nationality = | citizenship = | education = | occupation = Nurse | years_active = | known_for = | relations = | website = | profession = | field = | work_institutions = | specialism = | research_field = | notable_works = | prizes = | child = | module2 = | signature = }}
'''Mary Agnes Snively''' (12 November 1847 – 26 September 1933) was a Canadian nurse, later named as the first President of the [[Canadian Society of Superintendents of Training Schools for Nurses]].
==Work== Mary Agnes Snively was born in [[St. Catharines]], [[Ontario]], to Martin Snively, born in Ontario, and Susan Copeland, born in Ireland.<ref>''Ontario, Canada, Deaths and Deaths Overseas, 1869-1947''</ref> She was Lady Superintendent of Nurses at the Toronto General Hospital's School of Nursing from 1884 to 1910, where she established the first nursing student residence and a proper curriculum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.health.gov.on.ca/english/public/program/hhr/nurses/history.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-11-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027123417/http://www.health.gov.on.ca/english/public/program/hhr/nurses/history.html |archivedate=2007-10-27 |df= }}</ref>
She co-founded the [[International Council of Nurses]], and was its Honorary Treasurer from 1900 to 1904. She was also founder and president of the Canadian National Association of Trained Nurses from 1908 to 1912.
