{{Infobox person | name = Silvina Fabars | image = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = | birth_name = Silvina Fabars Gilall | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1944|02|22}} | birth_place = [[Santiago de Cuba]], [[Cuba]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = Cuban | other_names = | occupation = dancer, dance instructor | years_active = 1959–present | known_for = 2014 National Dance Prize of Cuba recipient | notable_works = }} {{Spanish name|Fabars|Gilall}}
'''Silvina Fabars''' (born 1944) is a Cuban folk dancer and ballerina who is the principal dancer of the [[National Folkloric Ensemble of Cuba]] and a noted folk dance instructor throughout Latin America and Europe. She has won numerous awards and recognition throughout her career including the ''Vanguardia Nacional'', the ''Distinción por la Cultura Nacional'' (Distinction of the National Culture), and the Alejo Carpentier Medal. In 2014, she was honored as the recipient of the National Dance Prize of Cuba.
==Biography== Silvina Fabars Gilall was born on 22 February 1944 in [[Santiago de Cuba]], [[Cuba]].<ref name="encyclopedia">{{cite web|title=Silvina Fabars Gilall|url=http://www.encaribe.org/es/article/silvina-fabars-gilall/1185|website=Enciclopedia de Historia y Cultura del Caribe|publisher=Comité Científico Técnico General de la enciclopedia|accessdate=6 February 2016|location=Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic|language=Spanish}}</ref> Her ancestry includes grandparents from [[Guinea]] and [[Ghana]], who helped raise her. As a child, she was taught to read and write by an aunt and was only able to attend elementary school for 2 or three years, as her labor was needed. She worked in the [[Sugarcane|cane fields]], planted sweet potatoes, picked coffee and hauled wood and water. She lived in a community of [[Haitians]] and learned their folk dances and [[patois]].<ref name="Díaz Rondón, 2014">{{cite news|last1=Díaz Rondón|first1=Francisnet|title=Silvina Fabars, una diosa de la danza|url=http://www.vanguardia.cu/cultura/2369-silvina-fabars-una-diosa-de-la-danza|accessdate=6 February 2016|publisher=''Vanguardia''|date=19 December 2014|location=Havana, Cuba|language=Spanish}}</ref> At the age of fourteen, she joined [[Fidel Castro]]'s rebel army in the [[Fidel Castro in the Cuban Revolution#Guerrilla war in the Sierra Maestra: 1956–58|Sierra Maestra]] and participated in the [[Cuban Revolution]].<ref name="encyclopedia" /><ref name="Cubadebate">{{cite news|title=Silvina Fabars, Premio Nacional de Danza 2014|url=http://www.cubadebate.cu/noticias/2014/04/19/silvina-fabars-premio-nacional-de-danza-2014/#.VrYFjtA2UVI|accessdate=6 February 2016|publisher=''[[Cubadebate]]''|date=19 April 2014|location=Havana, Cuba|language=Spanish}}</ref> In 1959, she began working at the airport in San Antonio de los Banos as a member of the legendary [[Mariana Grajales Coello|Mariana Grajales]] Women's Squad. Around the same time, she co-founded the first Cuban folk dancing company, known as the ''Ballet Folklórico de Oriente'' (Eastern Folk Dancing Company), where she performed as a singer and dancer until 1965.<ref name="encyclopedia" />
In 1966, Fabars was invited by the playwright and theater director, Eugenio Hernández Espinosa, to come to Havana and try out for the National Folkloric Ensemble ({{lang-es|Conjunto Folclórico Nacional}}) (CFN).<ref name="encyclopedia" /> She was hired as a singer, but after a serious accident which damaged her vocal chords, was offered a position as a hairdresser or makeup artist.<ref name="Díaz Rondón, 2014" /> Fabars was determined to continue performing as a dancer. Unfamiliar with the folk dances and traditions of the western part of Cuba, she studied with the anthropologist [[Fernando Ortiz Fernández]], as well as many of the company's premier dancers,<ref name="Sánchez, 2014">{{cite news|last1=Sánchez|first1=Martha|title=Silvina Fabars: an eternal queen of movement|url=http://oncubamagazine.com/culture/silvina-fabars-an-eternal-queen-of-movement/|accessdate=6 February 2016|publisher=''On Cuba Magazine''|date=3 January 2014|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref> such as Santiago Alfonso, Luisa Barroso, Nieves Fresneda, Zenaida Hernandez and Emilio O’Farrill.<ref name="Camejo, 2014">{{cite news|last1=Camejo|first1=Katia|others=Translator: Fanego, Pedro A.|title=Silvina Fabars, the Ebony Goddess|url=http://www.cadenahabana.cu/2014/05/07/silvina-fabars-the-ebony-goddess/|accessdate=6 February 2016|publisher=Radio Cadena Habana|date=7 May 2014|location=Havana, Cuba}}</ref> By 1978, she was offered a professorship to teach dance and the following year, she became the principal dancer of the CFN.<ref name="encyclopedia" /> Some of her most noted performances include ''Yoruba Iyessá'' by the Mexican choreographer [[Rodolfo Reyes Cortés]], which became a signature piece for Fabars; ''Ciclo Congo''; ''Arara'', which features spinning movements with a basket on her head;<ref name="Sánchez, 2014" /> and ''Rumbas y comparsas'', in which she was the zebra. She has performed in most of the repertoire productions of the CFN and has performed throughout the world, including in Algeria, Angola, Brazil, Canada, Colombia, England, France, Italy, Jamaica, Japan, Martinique, Mexico, Peru, Portugal, Spain, and the United States.<ref name="encyclopedia" />
In addition to teaching at the CFN, Fabars has taught throughout the country and helped establish groups and dance companies. As a teacher for the International Laboratory of Cuban Folklore which is a biannual course offered to teach Cuban dance, she has taught at the [[University of Alberta]], in Canada; [[University of Liverpool]] and [[University of London]] in England; at the Tokyo Cultural Center of Japan, as well as in Cuba,<ref name="encyclopedia" /> Russia and Venezuela.<ref name="Camejo, 2014" /> She spent two years in Venezuela helping the ministry of culture develop a folk dance company<ref name="encyclopedia" /> before returning to Cuba and establishing a folk dance training facility at the House of Culture in [[Camagüey]], where she currently teaches.<ref name="Cubadebate" />
Throughout her career, Fabars has won many honors. As part of the CFN, she has shared in awards which include the Golden Sandal trophy from Festidanza 1974 held in [[Arequipa]], Peru; in the Golden Barrel and Silver Necklace awarded by the 30th International Vineyard Festivities of Dijon, France (1975); the Silver Platter from the 1976 Billingham Folkloric Festival of [[Billingham]], England;{{sfn|Orovio|2004|p=148}} and the Golden Temple trophy from the 1988 Almond Blossom Festival of [[Agrigento]], [[Sicily]],<ref name="Vasallo, 2012">{{cite news|last1=Vasallo|first1=María del Carmen|title=Conjunto Folklórico Nacional: medio siglo en la escena|url=http://www.cubasi.cu/cubasi-noticias-cuba-mundo-ultima-hora/item/6352-conjunto-folklorico-nacional-medio-siglo-en-la-escena|accessdate=6 February 2016|publisher=''Cuba Sí''|date=7 May 2012|location=Havana, Cuba|language=Spanish}}</ref> among many others. Her individual awards include the ''Vanguardia Nacional'' (National Vanguard), the ''Distinción por la Cultura Nacional'' (Distinction of the National Culture), and the Alejo Carpentier Medal.<ref name="encyclopedia" /> In 2014, she was honored as the recipient of the National Dance Prize of Cuba.<ref name="Sánchez, 2014" /><ref name="Camejo, 2014" /><ref name="Díaz Rondón, 2014" />
